         <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1773-1841</unitdate>
         <abstract id="aspace_4405d264fa7bf505b290778051123c46">A collection of photostatic copies of letters (1779-1784) written to James Boyer, artilleryman and commissary officer, during the Revolutionary War. Correspondents include his brother, Peter Boyer, Samuel Hodgdon (1745-1824), Richard Frothingham (1748-1819), Ebenezer Stevens (1713-1798) and Henry Knox (1750-1806). Also included are photostatic copies of miscellaneous documents and papers "found in the Boston Post Office" relating to the Revolution.</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="dts_42092d61da8177b2e3d4b915fdd6721428e873b5" source="naf">
               <part>Boyer, James.</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
    
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_d5ee852aa891ad5c86e79e442f3ebe35">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Transferred from Beinecke Rare Book Library, 1973.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_b78767a6a3e436fd76f84915bca682bd">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_6bf4a5bf3cfbb204a9c6dadcee34c0cf">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>James Boyer Collection. Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_43587292f091ca99dd6b608e4a68c288">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The James Boyer collection consists of photostatic copies of letters (1779-1784) written to James Boyer during the Revolutionary War. James Boyer served in an artillery component under Ebenezer Stevens; he also served in a commissary office until the end of the war. Correspondents include Peter Boyer, his brother, a member of the Committee of Correspondence, Safety, and Inspection in Boston, Samuel Hodgdon (1745-1824), Richard Frothingham (1748-1819), and Ebenezer Stevens (1713-1798). Also included in this collection are photostatic copies of miscellaneous documents and papers relating to the Revolution which, in 1929, were described by the donor, Maj. Preston Brown, as being "found in the Boston Post Office."</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_b42da50cfaf4585c5398715adeda3d1d">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>Unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by the creator(s) of this collection are in the public domain. There are no restrictions on use. Copyright status for other collection materials is unknown. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.</p>  
      </userestrict>
